\begin_layout Chapter
Electrical transport properties of semiconductors and field-effect transistors
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Semiconductor-transport"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Semiconductors, as their name implies, are characterized by their conduction
 falling between that of a metal and an insulating material.
 The quantized energies of electron orbitals in a crystal and the interactions
 with nearby atoms dictate most of the properties of a semiconductor.
 The allowed energy levels form bands across the lattice and in momentum
 space that dictate the path of an moving electron.
 The relative location of the Fermi energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Fermi-energy"

\end_inset

 to various bands determines much of conductivity and device behavior.
 In metals the Fermi energy falls within energy-momentum band(s) allowing
 electrons to conduct with little resistance.
 Insulators have a large gap between bands, conventionally at least 3 electron
 volts (eV), and each far from the Fermi energy making conduction difficult
 without a very large energy excitation or electric field.
 Semiconductors fall in between metals and insulators and possess a band
 gap 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{G}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "band-gap"

\end_inset

 of a few electron volts (eV), where room temperature excitations are often
 enough to drive some conductivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Electrical transport in semiconductors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All real semiconductors break possess doped impurities, broken bonds, grain
 boundaries, edge states, and other forms of disorder.
 For practical devices we define the mobility 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "mobility"

\end_inset

 which is the average velocity at with an electron or hole can move through
 the crystal lattice from an electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Electric-field"

\end_inset

.
 The electrical conductivity of semiconductor, with a carrier concentration
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "carrier-concentration"

\end_inset

 of carriers with charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=q\mu n$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "conductivity"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "charge"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gap between the valance and conduction band can be either direct, where
 the respective max and minimum energy have the same momentum, or an indirect
 gap which requires the carrier to change momentum for the smallest energy
 jump between bands.
 Charge carriers can be the result of thermal excitations, so most semiconductor
s have an increased resistance at low temperatures.
 Photons can also excite electrons, or excited electrons can drop down the
 valance band and emit photons, giving rise to countless applications such
 as sensors and LEDs.
 In band transport model the electrons are free to move along the conduction
 band, and holes along the valance band, conducting through the crystal,
 as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hopping-transport"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a.
 The free carriers form extended states in the crystal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an intrinsic semiconductor the Fermi energy falls near the center of
 the gap, making it hard for carriers to be thermally excited as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "temperature"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Boltzman"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the temperature and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the Boltzmann constant, is only a few 10s of meV.
 Semiconductors are often doped to provide excess carriers and shift the
 bands relative to the Fermi energy.
 Doped semiconductors come in two flavors, n-type and p-type, that conduct
 primary using either electron or hole quasiparticles.
 Doping is often achieved by introducing other elements or using electric
 fields, and is used extensively in modern electronic devices.
\end_layout

