\begin_layout Standard
In slightly disordered semiconductors, a simple extension to the band-transport
 model is multiple trap and release (MTR).
 Small amounts of impurities introduce localized, shallow traps states within
 the band gap near the conduction (valance) band.
 Electrons (holes) continue to conduct along the band, temporarily getting
 stuck in the shallow traps and hopping out through thermal excitations,
 figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hopping-transport"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a.
 The effective mobility is reduced relative to the defect-free band mobility
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The MTR mobility is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{MTR}=\mu_{0}\exp\left(-\frac{E_{a}}{k_{B}T}\right)=\mu_{0}\frac{n_{band}}{n_{trap}+n_{band}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{a}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "activation-energy"

\end_inset

 is the average activation energy to hop from a trap to the band, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{band}$
\end_inset

 the density of carriers in the band, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{trap}$
\end_inset

 the density of trapped carriers.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
