\begin_layout Subsection
Variable range hopping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Variable range hopping (VRH) takes place is strongly disordered or amorphous
 semiconductors at low temperatures.
 In it, hopping takes place along a narrow band of localized states near
 the Fermi level, within the range of thermal excitations 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1k_{B}T$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hopping-transport"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a shows VRH near the conduction band in an n-type semiconductor.
 In Mott's original paper variable range hopping was restricted to three
 dimensions and low fields; later authors have extended this theory to be
 more general and drop those restrictions.
 Using the probability of hopping between two nearby states within this
 band, variable range hopping gives the conductivity equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=\sigma_{0}\exp\left(-T_{0}/T^{\beta_{vbh}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{vbh}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Variable-range-hopping-beta"

\end_inset

 depends on the model, and ranges between 0 and 1; and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a constant that combines several parameters of the crystal system.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mahan2010condensed,shklovskii1984variablerange"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 The mobility-temperature dependence is then given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{VHR}\propto\exp\left(-1/T^{\beta_{vbh}}\right)\,.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The two most common VHR models are Mott-VHR and Efros-Shklovskii-VRH.
 In Mott-VHR 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{vbh}=\frac{1}{d+1}$
\end_inset

, where d is the number of dimensions in the crystal, while the Efros-Shklovskii
-VRH model predicts that Coulomb interactions would open a gap in the density
 of states and gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{vbh}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 for all dimensions.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li2017transition,shklovskii1984variablerange"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Percolation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Percolation is used to model hopping in amorphous semiconductors using two
 similar approaches to simulate a large amount of disorder.
 Both models start with an infinite lattice of conducting bonds, carriers
 are free to hop along the bonds between atoms in the lattice and thus freely
 conduct as they would in a metal.
 In the bond variant, various bonds are blocked in the lattice preventing
 the carriers to move along those particular paths.
 Conversely, in the atom-site approach to percolation, atoms or sites that
 carriers can occupy are removed from the lattice preventing hopping along
 those paths.
 As long as the amount of bonds or sites removed 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Percolation-removed"

\end_inset

 remains below a critical fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Percolation-removed-critical"

\end_inset

, the carriers will be free to conduct through metallic regions of the lattice,
 albeit with reduced paths to traverse across the lattice.
 The fraction is dependent on the lattice structure and number of neighbors
 a carrier can hop to.
 When the fraction of removed bonds or states is low, the lattice will form
 small clusters of blocked regions, while larger 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 fractions will form larger insulating clusters with small holes for carriers
 to pass (percolate) through.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mahan2010condensed,shklovskii1984variablerange"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hopping-transport"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

b shows a disorder-free lattice, then the band and atomic approach to the
 percolation model.
 The mobility follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{PER}\propto\exp\left(-\frac{E_{t}-E_{F}\left(n,T\right)}{k_{B}T}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Percolation-transport-site-energy"

\end_inset

 is the highest energy of the sites that contribute to transport and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F}$
\end_inset

 is the Fermi energy
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Fermi-Energy"

\end_inset

.
 At low temperatures this approaches Efros-Shklovskii-VRH
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nenashev2019percolation,baranovskii2014theoretical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Metal-insulator transitions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Localization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In semiconductors and semiconductor devices the carriers can become localized
 as they travel through the lattice.
 Disorder in the crystal can trap or scatter carriers decreasing their conductiv
ity and mobility.
 The localization of carriers from disorder can even induce a crystal to
 undergo a metal-insulator transition (MIT).
 MITs display a shift in the resistivity-temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(T\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "resistivity"

\end_inset

 dependence, particularly at 0 K where the resistivity of the crystal changes
 from finite to infinite.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mahan2010condensed"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The origin of the MITs in disordered semiconductors is still an area of
 active study, with most models attributing MITs to the scattering of carriers
 off various sources of disorder, screening Coulomb forces from electron-electro
n interactions, or a combination of both.
 
\end_layout

