\begin_layout Subsection
Mobility edge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a system with a small amount of disorder, localized states will form
 a tail of allowed states extending into the band gap.
 This lets carriers hop between localized gap states or to-and-from the
 band.
 Mott proposed in three dimensions the density of states is continuous at
 the energy which carriers transition between localized and extended states.
 This critical transition energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}$
\end_inset

 is known as the mobility edge, figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Anderson-localization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

c.
 If the Fermi energy was below the mobility edge 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F}<E_{c}$
\end_inset

, the system will act as an insulator at low temperatures, or when 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F}>E_{c}$
\end_inset

 as a metal.
 The conductivity at 0 K follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma\left(T=0\,K\right)\propto\left(n-n_{c}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the critical carrier concentration, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a parameter representing disorder in the sample.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mahan2010condensed"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Recent work suggests that the mobility edge model may be valid in 2D materials
 with high mobility
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang2019redefining,lee2010band"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mott insulators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conventional band theory, at low temperatures electrons are bound to
 the sites of isolated donor atoms.
 To have free carriers an excitation must ionize one of those donor atoms.
 The excitation must be large enough to overcome the coulomb binding forces
 to the nucleus.
 When thermal (or other) excitations are sufficient, some distribution of
 the donors will ionize and contribute free electrons to the semiconductor.
 The electron-electron interactions between the itinerant carriers in the
 crystal and the bound electrons of the charged donor atom then act to screen
 the donor atom.
 The screening weakens the coulomb attraction of the free electrons to the
 donor atoms, letting the carriers remain unbound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If additional donors are added to the crystal, the additional electron-electron
 interactions will increase and further screen the donor atoms, reducing
 the Mott band gap.
 Eventually, adding enough donors to the system will cause the binding energy
 to reduce below what will form a bound state, making the material metallic
 in behavior.
 In the Mott model this critical transition is typically abrupt, occurring
 once the concentration of donors crosses the critical donor density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{dc}$
\end_inset

.
 If the donor concentration is above is above this threshold the semiconductor
 is metallic in nature and has a finite conductivity at 0 K, conversely,
 if the density of donors is below 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{dc}$
\end_inset

 then a Mott insulator forms and has infinite resistivity at 0 K.
 Mott found this critical density to be 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{dc}\simeq.24/a_{_{0}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the Bohr radius.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mott1949basis,mahan2010condensed"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

