\begin_layout Subsection
Percolation metal-insulator transition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The percolation MIT model starts with a disordered-metallic semiconductor,
 where electron-electron interactions screen the carriers from the disorder.
 If the density of free carriers in a semiconductor is lowered by a small
 amount, the screening of the carriers from defects decreases greatly in
 response, in a non-linear relationship.
 Near the transition, the itinerant carriers behave like a highly inhomogeneous
 electron gas, allowing free elections to become localized on the defects.
 To the electrons, the lattice appears as a series of hill and valley potentials
, causing the carriers to repel or collect in the respective lattice regions.
 If the density of carriers continues to decrease, the crystal disorder
 will continue to localize more electrons.
 This in turn removing paths for carriers though the semiconductor and decreasin
g conductivity.
 Eventually when the fraction of sites occupiable by or able to conduct
 free electrons, sinks below a critical threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{c}$
\end_inset

, the semiconductor becomes insulating (
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq p_{c}\leq1$
\end_inset

).
 At this point, the semiconductor is a series of isolated metallic islands.
