\begin_layout Standard
When constructing electronic devices with multiple materials we must consider
 the physical and chemical properties of the contact region between the
 two materials.
 Multiple phenomena can alter the materials near the contact region: the
 band structures of the individual crystal are shifted as a new preferred
 energy minimum is reached, chemical reactions take place between the two
 materials, the physical dimensions of one material shift to accommodate
 the other, etcetera.
 For most electronic transport applications, an ohmic contact is preferable
 as it takes less potential to form a current and has an easily predictable
 behavior.
 Ohmic contact is characterized by a linear relationship between the voltage
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Voltage"

\end_inset

 and current 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Current"

\end_inset

 given by the usual equation 
\begin_inset Formula $V=IR$
\end_inset

, where the resistance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Resistance"

\end_inset

 can depend on many factors like frequency and temperature.
 Ohmic contacts are usually found in a metal-metals junction as there is
 little band bending and metals conduct over a wide range of energy levels.
 Schottky contacts typically form at the interface between metals and semiconduc
tors, and have a non-linear relationship in 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The actual nature of Schottky contacts is complicated and no simple model
 exists for the interface of metal-semiconductors
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu2018approaching,tung2014physics"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 To predict the behavior of a metal-insulator junction one must numerically
 calculate the quantum mechanical states of the system, including the materials
 chemistry, and take into account the system's geometry
